      "content": "The argument leveraged by some contemporary theorists framed segregation as a rational economic management tool to maintain competitive standards. They posited that mixing disparate socioeconomic groups would inevitably create a drag on collective performance, as the lowest common denominator would dictate the standard for all institutions. Therefore, separation was presented as a logical administrative necessity—a way to ensure that high-achieving communities could dedicate resources and maintain their established levels of excellence without the perceived dilution or downward pressure of others. This framed it as a strategic resource allocation model rather than mere prejudice.",
